The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Threat mail prompts alert
                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                      Threat mail prompts alert
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                              
	Bhubaneswar, March 29: Security has been stepped up at important locations, including the secretariat, Assembly, Raj Bhavan and chief ministers residence, after Naveen Patnaik received an email, threatening to blow up his house and several other important places.        
	Director-general of police M.M. Praharaj said the special security battalion, raised for VIP security and protecting strategic installations, had been deployed in the city. We are planning to develop Bhubaneswar as a high-security zone. A high-level committee, headed by chief secretary, has been constituted to look into the matter, said Praharaj.         
	A mail, sent from plga orissa.gov.in, reached the official id of the chief minister last evening. Signed by the central military commission of the Peoples Liberation Guerrilla Army, the mail threatened to blow up Naveen Nivas, the residence of chief minister, and target in Bhubaneswar, Cuttack and Puri.        
	A high-level meeting, chaired by the chief minister here today, discussed follow-up measures.        
	Praharaj said a case had been registered with the cyber crime police station and the matter was being investigated by wing. We are verifying the authenticity and source of the mail, he said.        
	Bhubaneswar-Cuttack police commissioner B.K. Sharma said: We have expertise to investigate into such matters. If necessary, we will take the assistance of experts.        
	The home department is framing rules to deal with cyber crimes, Sharma said.                                                                                                                                                          
